<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-02">
  <title>Egyptian and Babylonian Mathematics (2.1-2.6)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-History-of-Egypt">
    <title>History of Egypt</title>

    <p>
      The empire of Egypt, located in the fertile Nile river valley, was one of the world's earliest civilizations. The empire was founded around 3000 B.C and lasted until around 300 B.C. when it was conquered by Alexander the Great. The Egyptians built many impressive monuments such as the Spinx and the pyramids which required precise mathematical calculations. They also had highly sophisticated agricultural techniques and an effective system of medicine. Their pyramids are some of the oldest monuments that are still standing, and they are predicted to outlast modern skyscrapers.
    </p>

    <p>
      Archaeological evidence shows that Egyptian numerals date back to at least 3200 B.C. The Great Pyramid was built around 2600 B.C. For the next 3800 years it was the tallest man made structure in the world. The ratio of the pyramid to the height is <m>\frac{44}{7}</m> which is approximately <m>2\pi</m> leading some to believe that the Egyptians knew about <m>\pi</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Around 1850 B.C. a text containing 25 mathematical problems known as the Moscow Papyrus was written. It is one of the most important sources that we have about Egyptian Mathematics; however, it is very different from our modern mathematics textbooks. Instead of explaining the technique behind solving a problem, it simply lists problems and works out the solution. This creates a puzzle for math historians to determine the breath of Egyptian mathematical knowledge. Around 1650 B.C. another mathematical text, the Rhind Papyrus, was written. It too provides insight into Egyptian mathematical knowledge and is written similarly to the Moscow Papyrus.
    </p>

    <p>
      In 1799 A.D. The Rosetta stone was discovered by the French military engineers working for Napoleon. The stone contains the same message written in Hieroglyphics, Egyptian demotic, and Ancient Greek, and provided a way to decipher the Hieroglyphics which had fallen out of use centuries earlier.
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Egyptian-Arithmetic">
    <title>Egyptian Arithmetic</title>

    <p>
      As mentioned previously, Egyptians used an additive base 10 numeral system. Later an alternate system was developed with more symbols so that large numbers could be expressed with fewer signs.
    </p>

    <p>
      In many ways Egyptian mathematics is additive and multiplication is always thought of as repeated addition. They used an interesting technique to easily multiply 2 numbers. They would write one number as a sum of powers of 2, then double the other number as many times necessary and add the correct numbers together.
    </p>

    <p>
      For example to multiply 42 times 37, they would first write <m>37 = 32 + 4 + 1</m>. Then they would compute
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp 1 \cdot 42 = 42</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 2 \cdot 42 = 84</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 4 \cdot 42 = 168</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 8 \cdot 42 = 336</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 16 \cdot 42 = 672</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 32 \cdot 42 = 1344</mrow>
      </md>
      Finally they add <m>1344+ 168+42 = 1554</m>. So <m>42\cdot 37 = 1554</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Use Egyptian multiplication to find <m>24\cdot 27</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      The Egyptian multiplication method can also be used to solve division problems. Suppose the Pharaoh wants to divide <m>1652</m> bushels of wheat to give to <m>75</m> officials. How much wheat should each official receive?
    </p>

    <p>
      First we double <m>75</m> repeatedly until we find a multiple larger than <m>1652</m>

      <md>
        <mrow> \amp 1 \cdot 75 = 75</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 2 \cdot 42 = 150</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 4 \cdot 42 = 300</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 8 \cdot 42 = 600</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 16 \cdot 42 = 1200</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 32 \cdot 42 = 2400</mrow>
      </md>

      Since <m>1200+300+150 = 1650</m> which leaves <m>2</m> left over it follows that <m>\frac{1652}{75} = 22 + \frac{2}{75}</m>
      
    </p>

    <p>
      The Egyptians would then rewrite <m>\frac{2}{75}</m> as a sum of unit fractions. In the next section, we will discuss unit fractions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Use Egyptian division to divide 84,136 by 239.
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Unit-Fractions">
    <title>Unit Fractions</title>

    <p>
      One thing that is unique about Egyptian mathematics is their use of <term>unit fractions</term>. A unit fraction is a fraction whose numerator is <m>1</m> such as <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> or <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>. With the exception of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> all fractions were written as <m>\frac{1}{n}</m>. Other fractions can be written as a sum of unit fractions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Special symbols were developed for the fractions <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>, <m>\frac{1}{8}</m>, <m>\frac{1}{16}</m>, <m>\frac{1}{32}</m>, and <m>\frac{1}{64}</m>. These are called Horus-eye fractions based on a theory that the symbols were based on parts of a symbol called the eye of Horus. 
    </p>

    <p>
      The Egyptians would try to represent fractions using Horus-eye fractions. If there was a remainder left over, it would be represented using other unit fractions.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The Ancient Egyptian scribes seemed to have developed certain rules about unit fractions. For example <m>\frac{2}{35}</m> was represented as <m>\frac{1}{30}+ \frac{1}{42}</m>. Based on the examples we've discovered it seems that they chose unit fraction representations based on the following guidelines
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Small denominators were preferred over larger ones
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Fewer unit fractions were preferred over many unit fractions
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Unit fractions were never repeated, so you couldn't write <m>\frac{2}{35}</m> as <m>\frac{1}{35}+\frac{1}{35}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Even denominators were preferred over odd ones
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Smaller denominators were written first
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
      The reason for some of these rules comes from the Egyptian terms used for fractions. The Egyptian symbols that we would translate as <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> are more accurately translated as "the third part" and "the fourth part". Thus these symbols don't easily lend themselves to representing fractions like <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>, which is why they used unit fractions. This is also why they didn't repeat unit fractions when using them to represent other quantities: there can only be one third part of a quantity! 
    </p>

    <p>
      To express a number as a sum of unit fractions following these guidelines, you can use the so called <term>Brute Force Method</term>. Given a unit fraction such as <m>\frac{11}{15}</m> we first find the fraction with the smallest denominator that is less than it, in this case <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> to be our first unit fraction. Subtracting <m>\frac{11}{15}-\frac{1}{2} = \frac{7}{30}</m> so we repeat the process with the remainder term <m>\frac{7}{30}</m>. The unit fraction with the smallest denominator that is smaller than <m>\frac{7}{30}</m> is <m>\frac{1}{5}</m> and <m>\frac{7}{30}-\frac{1}{5} = \frac{1}{30}</m>. Hence <m>\frac{11}{15} = \frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5}+\frac{1}{30}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Represent the number <m>\frac{3}{7}</m> using unit fractions
    </p>

    <p>
      It can be proven, although we will not do so, that every rational number can be represented as a finite sum of unit fractions using the Brute Force Method.
    </p>

    <p>
      At the Beginning of the Rhind Papyrus is a table giving breakdowns of various rational numbers with a numerator of <m>2</m> and an odd denominator into unit fractions. Egyptian scribes made use of these tables to simplify calculations with unit fractions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Multiplication of unit fractions can be done by the method of doubling. For example to multiply <m>5+\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5}</m> we make a doubling table:
      <md>
        <mrow> \amp 1 \cdot 1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5} = 1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 2 \cdot 1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5} = 3 + \frac{2}{5}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp 4 \cdot 1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5} = 6 + \frac{4}{5}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp \frac{1}{2} \cdot 1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5} = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{4} + \frac{1}{10}</mrow>
      </md>
      
    </p>

    <p>
      Adding the first row and the last two rows gives that the product of <m>4+\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{5}</m> is <m>9+\frac{1}{4}+\frac{1}{10}</m>. In modern notation, we have shown that <m>5 \frac{1}{2}\cdot 1 \frac{7}{10} = 9\frac{7}{20}</m>
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Egyptian-Algebra">
    <title>Egyptian Algebra</title>

    <p>
      The Rhind Papyrus contains 84 problems of various kinds that have been translated into English. Part of the difficulty of understanding Egyptian mathematics is trying to interpret what is was that the scribe was trying to solve. For example Problem 40 literally reads
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>
          Loaves 100 for man 5, <m>\frac{1}{7}</m> of the 3 above to man 2 those below. What is the difference of share?
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    

    <p>
      Historians believe that this problem means that 100 loaves of bread is to be divided unequally among five men so that the two men who receive the least amount of loaves receive <m>\frac{1}{7}</m> of the amount of the other three men and each man receives a fixed number of loaves more than the next man. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Problem 24 illustrates the Egyptian method for solving equations. It reads
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          A quantity, <m>\frac{1}{7}</m> is added to it, becomes it: <m>19</m>
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        In modern notation, this is asking us to find a number such that when <m>\frac{1}{7}</m> of it is added to it equals <m>19</m> or to solve the equation <m>x+\frac{1}{7}x = 19</m>
      </p>

      <p>
        The solution given in the Rhind Papyrus is to first guess that <m>x=7</m>. This guess is chosen because it eliminates the fraction. However if <m>x=7</m> then <m>x+\frac{1}{7}x = 8</m>, which is not the correct answer. However, the scribe recognizes that this  is <m>\frac{19}{8}</m> of the correct answer and thus the correct answer is <m>7 \cdot \frac{19}{8} = \frac{133}{8}</m> which he expresses using unit fractions. More accurately, he first divides <m>19</m> by <m>8</m> and then multiplies by <m>7</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        This solution technique of multiplying by a guess and then determining the correct solution from the incorrect guess is known as the <term>Method of False Position</term>
      </p>

      <p>
        Example: Problem 26 from the Rhind Papyrus asks for the solution of <m>x+ \frac{x}{4} = 15</m>. Solve this using the method of false position.
      </p>
    
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Egyptian-Geometry">
    <title>Egyptian Geometry</title>

    <p>
      The Greek Historian Herodotus wrote that the Greeks learned the art of measurement from the Egyptians. Another Greek author, Proclus, in summarizing Greek geometry before Euclid wrote
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Thales, who had traveled to Egypt, was the first to introduce this science into Greece.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      According to Herodotus, if the Nile overflowed its bank and made land unsuitable for growing crops, then the Pharaoh's officials would calculate the proportion of land that was destroyed and reduce the taxation on the land by that amount.
    </p>

    <p>
      26 of the 110 problems from the Moscow Papyrus and Rhind Papyrus are geometric. 
    </p>

    <p>
      Problem 50 of the Rhind Papyrus deals with finding the area of a circle. It states
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Example of a round field of diameter 9 khet. What is its area?
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      The solution given is
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Take away <m>\frac{1}{9}</m> of the diameter, namely <m>1</m>; the remainder is <m>8</m>. Multiply <m>8</m> by <m>8</m>; it makes <m>64</m>. Therefore it contains <m>64</m> setat of land
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      The scribe's process for finding area is essentially to multiply the diameter by <m>\frac{8}{9}</m> and square the result. That is
      <md>
        A = \left( \frac{8d}{9}\right)^2 = \frac{64}{81}d^2
      </md>
      
    </p>

    <p>
      Comparing this with the formula for the exact area of a circle
      <md>
        A = \pi r^2 = \frac{\pi}{4}d^2
      </md>
      we find that 
      <md>
        \frac{64}{81}d^2 = \frac{\pi}{4}d^2
      </md>
      so that <m>\pi = \frac{256}{81} \approx 3.16</m> which is good enough for most applications.
    </p>

    <p>
      Problem 14 of the Moscow Papyrus involves the volumes of a truncated pyramid, also called a frustrum. It reads
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Example of calculating a truncated pyramid. If you are told: a truncated pyramid of 6 for the vertical height by 4 on the base by 2 on the top: You are to square this 4; result 16. You are to double 4; result 8. You are to square this 2; result 4. You are to add the 16 and the 8 and the 4; result 28. You are to take <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> of 6; result 2. You are to take 28 twice; result 56. See, it is of 56. You will find it right.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      This example illustrates that the Egyptians were familiar with the formula to find the volume of a truncated pyramid with vertical height <m>h</m> whose top and bottom are squares of length <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>:
      <md>
        V = \frac{h}{3}(a^2+ab+b^2)
      </md>
      although historians are not sure how they deduced this.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Suppose that a frustum has a height of 9 ft, and the lengths of the square bases are <m>10</m> ft and <m>3</m> ft. What is the volume of the frustum?
    </p>

    <p>
      Problem 10 of the Moscow Papyrus deals with finding the area of a <em>nbet</em>. The word <em>nbet</em> appears in no other Egyptian manuscript so we aren't quite sure what type of an object it refers to. Based on the solution given, it seems to refer to either a hemisphere with diameter <m>4.5</m> or a semicylinder whose height is half its diameter. The problem reads:
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Example of calculating a <em>nbet</em>. You are given a <em>nbet</em> with a mouth of <m>4+\frac{1}{2}</m>. What is its surface?
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      And the solution is given
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Take <m>\frac{1}{9}</m> of <m>9</m> since the <em>nbet</em> is half an egg-shell. You get <m>1</m>. Calculate the remainder which is <m>8</m>. Calculate <m>\frac{1}{9}</m> of <m>8</m>. You get <m>\frac{2}{3}+\frac{1}{6}+\frac{1}{18}</m>. Find the remainder of this <m>8</m> after subtracting <m>\frac{2}{3}+\frac{1}{6}+\frac{1}{18}</m>. You get <m>7+\frac{1}{9}</m>. Multiply <m>7+\frac{1}{9}</m> by <m>4+\frac{1}{2}</m>. You get <m>32</m>. Behold this is its area! You have found it correctly.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      In modern notation the solution computes the area as
      <md>
        A = (((2\times d)\times\frac{8}{9})\times \frac{8}{9}) \times d = \frac{128}{81}d^2
      </md>
      
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the same as the exact formula for the area of a hemisphere 
      <md>
        A = \frac{1}{2}\pi d^2
      </md>
      where <m>\frac{256}{81}</m> is used as an approximation for <m>\pi</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      This is possibly the earliest calculation of a curved surface. It would be take another 1500 years before the formula for the surface area of a sphere was rediscovered by the Greek mathematician Archimedes.
    </p>

    <p>
      Find the surface area of a hemisphere with diameter of <m>5</m>m using both the Egyptian formula and the modern formula. 
    </p>
    
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Egyptian-Mathematics-as-Applied-Arithmetic">
    <title>Egyptian Mathematics as Applied Arithmetic?</title>

    <p>
      On page 50 of Burton's book <em>History of Mathematics: An Introduction</em> he writes
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Looking at the extant Egyptian mathematical manuscripts as a whole, we find that they are nothing but collections of practical problems of the kind that are associated with business and administrative transactions. The teaching of the art of calculation appears to be the chief element in the problems. Everything is stated in terms of specific numbers, and nowhere does one find a trace of what might properly be called a theorem or a general rule of procedure. If the criterion for scientific mathematics is the existence of the concept of proof, the ancient Egyptians confined themselves to "applied arithmetic".
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      In contrast A.B. Chase wrote
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        A careful study of the Rhind Papyrus convinced me several years ago that this work is not a mere selection of practical problems especially useful to determine land values, and that the Egyptians were not a nation of shopkeepers, interested only in that which they could use. Rather I believe that they studied mathematics and other subjects for their own sakes.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      Thinking about these two quotes, answer the following questions:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            What evidence can you give to support each of these arguments?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Which argument do you find most convincing? Why?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Baylonian-Clay-Tablets">
    <title>Baylonian Clay Tablets</title>

    <p>
      The empire of Babylonia was located in the southern part of Mesopotamia, in what is now modern day Iraq. It was established around 1895 B.C. and fell in 539 B.C.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Babylonians were accomplished astronomers and architects. The modern zodiac was first described by the Babylonians and the Hanging Gardens of Babylon was one of the seven wonders of the ancient world.
    </p>

    <p>
      Archaeologists in Mesopotamia have unearthed over 500,000 inscribed clay tablets. Some of these contain mathematical tables and formulas. However, it wasn't until we were able to translate the cuneiform text that we were able to understand what was written on them.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Babylonians were familiar with the rules of measurements for common shapes. They knew the rules for areas of rectangles, triangles, and trapezoids, and the volumes of rectangluar prisms. They measured the circumference of a circle as 3 times the diameter and the area as <m>1/12</m> the square of circumference. Both are true if <m>\pi=3</m>. They were aware that this is an approximation because another tablet gives a better approximation of 3.125 
    </p>

    <p>
      Babylonians used a base 60 positional numeral system. Remnants of this system survive in modern times. There are 60 minutes in an hour, 60 seconds in a minute, and a complete revolution is 360 degrees.
    </p>

    <p>
      The early Babylonians had a unit of distance now called the Babylonian mile which is about 7 modern miles. Later this became a unit of time as well, defined as the time it takes to travel a Babylonian mile. Babylonian astronomers calculated that a complete day is 12 Babylonian miles. Thus a complete revolution of the sky is 12 Babylonian miles. For convenience the Babylonian mile was divided into 30 equal parts, so for the Babylonians there were <m>12\cdot 30 = 360</m> equal parts in a complete revolution, which is why a complete revolution is 360 degrees.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Babylonians were familiar with the Pythagorean Theorem. A translation of one Babylonian tablet reads as follows.
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          4 is the length and 5 is the diagonal. What is the breadth? Its size is not known. 4 times 4 is 16. 5 times 5 is 25. You take 16 from 25 and there remains 9. What times what shall I take in order to get 9? 3 times 3 is 9. 3 is the breadth.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </p>

    <p>
      The tablet below is known as Plimpton 322. It was first believed to be a record of transactions until 1945, when mathematicians realized the patterns in the list.
    </p>






    <p>
      Here is the tablet written with modern digits. The numbers are still base 60, so the 2nd and 3rd columns of the 1st row read 119 and 169 in base 10.
    </p>







<p>
  119 and 169 may not seem to be special numbers, but if a right triangle has length 119 and hypotenuse 169, then the missing side is 120.
</p>

<p>
  A set of 3 positive integers, like <m>(3,4,5)</m> which can be the sides of a right triangle is known as a Pythagorean triple.
</p>

<p>
  For each row the 2nd and 3rd columns are a leg and hypotenuse of a integer sided right triangle, with 4 exceptions. These exceptions can be explained by typos. For example in row 9 column 2 should be <m>8,1</m> instead of <m>9,1</m>.
</p>

<p>
  A Pythagorean triple is said to be primitive if the three numbers contain no common factors. For example <m>(3,4,5)</m> is primitive but <m>(6,8,10)</m> is not. In the tablet, all the triples except the ones in lines 11 and 15 are primitive.
</p>

<p>
  A theorem in mathematics says that all primitive Pythagorean triples are given by the equations <m>a=2uv</m> <m>b= u^2-v^2</m> and <m>c=u^2+v^2</m>, where <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> have no common factors, are not both odd or both even, and <m>u &gt;v</m>.
</p>

<p>
  Example: Suppose <m>u=2</m> and <m>v=1</m>. What primitive Pythagorean triple do we obtain?
</p>

<p>
  Example: Find a Pythagorean triple for a triangle with a side that measures 20 m.
</p>

<p>
  Example: Find a Pythagorean triple for a triangle with a side that measures 63 m.
</p>

<p>
  The first column is found to be the value of <m>(\frac{c}{a})^2</m>. In order for this quotient to have a finite sexagesimal expansion (meaning that it terminates) <m>a</m> needs to have only 2, 3, and 5 as prime factors. Since <m>a = 2uv</m>, this means that <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> also need to have 2, 3, and 5 as prime factors.
</p>

<p>
  The first column represents <m>\sec^2 B</m>, where <m>B</m> is the angle opposite side <m>b</m>. Moreover these secants decrease by almost exactly <m>\frac{1}{60}</m> as one passes from one line to the other. The corresponding angle decreases from 45 degrees to 31 degrees. Likely there were similar tables for 30 degrees to 16 degrees and for 15 degrees to 1 degree.
</p>

    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Babylonian-Treatment-of-Quadratic-Equations">
    <title>Babylonian Treatment of Quadratic Equations</title>

    <p>
      It is evident from the multitude of clay tablets that have been found that the Babylonians knew how to solve quadratic equations. These problem tablets contain no general formula, but solutions for a wide variety of problems that illustrate that a general technique was known. For example, Problem 2 on the tablet BM 13901 reads
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          I took away my square-side from inside the area and it was <m>14,30</m>. You put down <m>1</m> the projection. You break off half of <m>1</m>. You combine <m>0;30</m> and <m>0;30</m>. You add <m>0;15</m> to <m>14,30</m>. <m>14,30;15</m> squares <m>29;30</m>. You add <m>0;30</m> which you combined to <m>29;30</m> so that the square-side is <m>30</m>. 
        </p>
      </blockquote>  
    </p>

    <p>
      To understand the problem and its solution, let us substitute some variables into the problem. Let <m>x</m> be the unknown (the side of the square), <m>b</m> the coefficient <m>1</m> and <m>c</m> the number <m>14;30</m>. Then the problem can be written as
      <md>
        x^2-bx=c
      </md>
      so this problem is a quadratic equation.
    </p>

    <p>
      The solution consists of the following steps
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            put down <m>b</m> the coefficient, <m>1</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            break off half the coefficient to give <m>\frac{1}{2}b</m>, <m>0;30</m> 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            combine it with itself to get <m>(\frac{1}{2}b)^2</m>, <m>0;15</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Add this to the original number <m>c</m> to give <m>c+(\frac{1}{2}b)^2</m>, <m>14,30;15</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            find what it is the square of, to give <m>\sqrt{c+(\frac{1}{2}b)^2}</m>, <m>29;30</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            add this to the halved coefficient <m>\frac{1}{2}b</m> to get <m>\frac{1}{2}b + \sqrt{c+(\frac{1}{2}b)^2}</m>, <m>30</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            This is the answer.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
      Notice how the above computation follows the same procedure that we would use to solve a quadratic equation by completing the square. This demonstrates that Babylonian scribes were familiar with this technique for solving quadratic equations. Also notice that the positive square root was the only one that was chosen and the answer given by taking the negative square root is not considered. This makes sense because we are dealing with the side of a square which must be positive, but it also illustrates that Babylonian mathematicians did not allow for negative number solutions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another typical Babylonian problem involves perimeters and areas of rectangles. Specifically given the semiperimeter <m>x+y=a</m> and the area <m>xy=b</m> of a rectangle, we are asked to find the length <m>x</m> and width <m>y</m>. This requires the solution of a system of two equations with two unknowns and can be solved by substitution.
    </p>

    <p>
      However, the Babylonians used a different method to solve these types of problems, similar to the Egyptian method of false position. They began by assuming that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are equal; that is <m>x = y = \frac{a}{2}</m>, which solves the first equation but not the second. Since the sum of <m>x+y</m> is fixed, increasing <m>x</m> must decrease <m>y</m> by the same amount. Thus <m>x= \frac{a}{2}+z</m> and <m>y = \frac{a}{2}-z</m> must be the solutions for some value of <m>z</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Substituting these into the second equation gives
      <md>
        (\frac{a}{2}+z)(\frac{a}{2}-z) = b
      </md>
      which simplifies to 
      <md>
        (\frac{a}{2})^2 -z^2 = b.
      </md>
      Hence

      <md>
        z^2 = (\frac{a}{2})^2 - b
      </md>
       and so
       <md>
        z = \sqrt{(\frac{a}{2})^2 - b}
       </md>
       
    </p>

    <p>
      As before the negative root was not considered. Thus the solution is found to be 
      <md>
        x = \frac{a}{2} + \sqrt{(\frac{a}{2})^2 - b}
      </md>
      and

      <md>
        y = \frac{a}{2} - \sqrt{(\frac{a}{2})^2 - b}
      </md>
      
      
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Use the Babylonian method to determine the length and width of a rectangle whose semiperimeter is 29 meters and whose area is 208 square meters.
    </p>



    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Babylonian-Method">
    <title>Babylonian Method</title>

    <p>
      The following tablet gives an approximation of <m>\sqrt{2}</m> using base 60 digits. In base 10, this represents the decimal <m>1.41421296</m>
    </p>






    <p>
      The actual value of <m>\sqrt{2}</m> is about <m>1.41421356</m>, so the Babylonian approximation has an error of <m>0.000000597</m>. The Babylonian approximation is the most accurate approximation with 3 decimal places in base 60.
    </p>

    <p>
      No one knows for sure how the Babylonians computed <m>\sqrt{2}</m> so accurately, but many people believe that they used a form of what's now called the Babylonian method (also called Heron's method), which was first written down by the Greek Mathematician Hero of Alexandria in 60 A.D.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Babylonian method is used to approximate <m>\sqrt{S}</m> where <m>S</m> is a positive number.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Choose a guess <m>x_0</m> (The closer to <m>\sqrt{S}</m> the better)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>x_{n+1} = \dfrac{1}{2}\left(x_n + \dfrac{S}{x_n} \right)</m>. This is the average of <m>x_n</m> and <m>\dfrac{S}{x_n}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Repeat until desired accuracy is obtained.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            In the Babylonian Method, if <m>x_n= \sqrt{S}</m> then <m>x_n = \dfrac{S}{x_n} </m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now suppose that <m>x_n &lt; \sqrt{S}</m>. Then <m>\dfrac{S}{x_n} &gt; \sqrt{S}</m>. By averaging these 2 values, you get something closer to square root of <m>x_n</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Likewise if <m>x_n &gt; \sqrt{S}</m>. Then <m>\dfrac{S}{x_n} &lt; \sqrt{S}</m> and by averaging these 2 values, you get something closer to square root of <m>x_n</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Example: Use the Babylonian Method to approximate <m>\sqrt{2}</m> accurately to 3 decimal places.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

</section>
